Wash and dry all produce. Core and seed @Roma Tomato{1}(seeded), then cut into ½-inch
pieces. Zest @Lemon{1}(zested) until you have 1 tsp zest, then cut into wedges.
Trim, then thinly slice @Scallions{2}(sliced), keeping greens and whites separate.
Mince or grate @Garlic{2%cloves}(minced).

In a small #bowl{}, stir together @Sour Cream{4%tbsp}, half the lemon zest, and a
few squeezes of lemon juice (to taste—start with about ¼ of the lemon and go up
from there). Season with @Salt{} and @Pepper{}. Taste and add more lemon zest or
juice, if desired.

Melt @Butter{1%tbsp} in a medium #pot{} over medium-high heat. Add @Israeli Couscous{½%cup}
and cook, stirring occasionally, until lightly toasted, ~{2-3%minutes}. Add
1 cup water, then bring to a boil. Lower heat slightly and let simmer until
al dente, ~{7-9%minutes}. Remove couscous from pot and set aside.

Heat another @Butter{1%tbsp} and a large drizzle of @Vegetable Oil{} in pot used
for couscous over medium-high heat. Once butter is melted, add scallion whites
and tomato. Cook, stirring frequently, until slightly softened, ~{2-3%minutes}.
Lower heat to medium and add garlic. Cook until fragrant, about ~{1%minute}.
Stir in couscous. Season with salt and pepper, then remove pot from heat.

Heat a drizzle of oil in a medium #pan{} over medium-high heat (use a #nonstick
pan{} if you have one). Pat @Skin-On Salmon Fillets{10%oz} dry with a #paper towel{}.
Season all over with salt, pepper, and @Fry Seasoning{1%tbsp}. Add to pan
skin-side down. Cook until skin is crisp, ~{4-6%minutes}. Flip and cook to desired
doneness, ~{2-3%minutes} more.

Fluff couscous with a #fork{}, then stir in half the scallion greens. Divide
between #plates{}, along with salmon. Drizzle salmon with a spoonful of crema.
Sprinkle with remaining scallion greens. Serve with any remaining lemon wedges
and crema on the side.

> Arrange the salmon fillets skin-side up to keep the skin crisp.